    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Diagnostics Model Years 1999-2000 - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEM DIAGNOSTICS -
        Circuit Function And Diagnostics - Voltage Reference (VREF)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="P17503001" svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Voltage Reference (V
            <subscript>REF</subscript>)
        </title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Circuit Functions</title>
            <figure id="f17503100" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figEG1/EG1255A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for Voltage Reference</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Electronic Control Module (ECM) sends a 5 &#177; 0.5 volt reference signal to the three wire
                engine and vehicle sensors in the electronic control system. The ECM determines pressure, speed,
                position, and other variables for engine and vehicle functions by comparing the regulated 5 &#177; 0.5
                volts sent to the sensors with signals sent back from the sensors.
            </para>
            <para>Three voltage reference circuits are used in the electronic control system:</para>
            <para>V
                <subscript>REF</subscript>
                B - for Chassis Sensors
            </para>
            <para>V
                <subscript>REF</subscript>
                C - for Body Builder Sensors
            </para>
            <para>V
                <subscript>REF</subscript>
                D - for Engine Sensors
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            <para>Diagnostic Trouble Codes are not directly set for voltage reference signals, but a sensor fault in a
                voltage reference circuit can set an Out of Range High or Out of Range Low Diagnostic Trouble Code.
                Multiple high or low codes usually indicate V
                <subscript>REF</subscript>
                faults or signal ground faults.
            </para>
            <para>A voltage reference signal shorted to ground will cause the ECM to reset causing either a stumble or
                no start condition.
            </para>
